// Proposed by 🔬 ledger during AUDIT-OWN. Dry-run before filing (see backlog).
//
// Two new must_fail/control PAIRS. Each negative probe ships a positive control running
// the SAME argv AND the SAME env, asserting a literal that command genuinely prints —
// invariant (b). A pair whose control is vacuous is a green check that means nothing.

// --- G16: `sensitive = true` masks the VALUE, not the variable ---------------
// The existing fixture cannot show this: `ghp_FIXTURE_SENTINEL` is not a substring of
// `plain_FIXTURE_CONTROL`, so no bleed is observable. An `env` overlay fixes that with
// NO new fixture: PKR_VAR_pub injects the secret's value into a DIFFERENT, non-sensitive
// variable, and packer redacts it there too. This is the claim that makes G16's
// "never mark `admin` sensitive" warning true rather than merely plausible.
{"id":"g16-sensitive-masks-value-inside-unrelated-variable","kind":"cli-help","file":"specs/macos-ci/13-build-secrets.md","argv":["packer","inspect","tests/fixtures/packer-sensitive"],"env":{"PKR_VAR_pub":"ghp_FIXTURE_SENTINEL_AND_MORE"},"expect":"<sensitive>_AND_MORE","claim":"packer's sensitive=true redacts the VALUE wherever it appears, including inside a different, NON-sensitive variable: overriding var.pub to `ghp_FIXTURE_SENTINEL_AND_MORE` prints `<sensitive>_AND_MORE`. Masking is a substring rewrite over the output, not a property of the variable. This is why marking a common word (`admin`, G8's public default password) sensitive would rewrite every occurrence of that word in every log. POSITIVE CONTROL for g16-injected-secret-never-prints-in-unrelated-variable: same argv, same env, and it proves the command emits output at all."}
{"id":"g16-injected-secret-never-prints-in-unrelated-variable","kind":"cli-help","must_fail":true,"file":"specs/macos-ci/13-build-secrets.md","argv":["packer","inspect","tests/fixtures/packer-sensitive"],"env":{"PKR_VAR_pub":"ghp_FIXTURE_SENTINEL_AND_MORE"},"expect":"ghp_FIXTURE_SENTINEL_AND_MORE","claim":"the sensitive value does not survive being smuggled into a non-sensitive variable: the injected literal never reaches packer's output. Alone this is unfalsifiable — an empty output satisfies it equally. Paired with g16-sensitive-masks-value-inside-unrelated-variable, which runs the SAME argv and SAME env and asserts `<sensitive>_AND_MORE` IS printed."}

// --- the verifier's own must_fail soundness ----------------------------------
// Found this run: `_read` raising FileNotFoundError used to return a PLAIN failure
// (`missing: ...`), which `must_fail` inverted into a PASS. So DELETING a control's
// target file turned that control green. CONTROL-12-line-607-does-not-exist is exactly
// such a claim. Fixed by prefixing UNREACHABLE. This claim pins the fix.
{"id":"verify-claims-missing-file-is-unreachable","kind":"file-contains","file":"specs/macos-ci/12-tooling-and-agent-loop.md","target":"tools/verify_claims.py","expect":"UNREACHABLE: missing file:","claim":"an absent target file yields an UNREACHABLE-prefixed failure, which must_fail never inverts. Without this prefix, deleting a control's target file turns the control GREEN — a must_fail file-line claim on a missing file 'passes' for the wrong reason. Guards CONTROL-12-line-607-does-not-exist against exactly that."}

